{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16470"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16470"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.05,0.15,0.2,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9161"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60343"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old male presents with back pain and increased urinary frequency after testing positive for Influenza. Neurological examination revealed power 4/5 at bilateral lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures is primarily involved in myelitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spinal cord parenchyma","Dura mater","Epidural space","Subarachnoid space","Subdural space"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMyelitis refers to inflammation specifically affecting the \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord parenchyma\u003C/strong\u003E. The term is derived from \u0027myel-\u0027 (referring to spinal cord) and \u0027-itis\u0027 (meaning inflammation). The clinical presentation typically includes motor weakness, sensory changes, and autonomic dysfunction corresponding to the level of spinal cord involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edura mater\u003C/strong\u003E is the outermost meningeal layer. Inflammation of the dura mater would be termed pachymeningitis, which presents differently from myelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural space\u003C/strong\u003E lies between the dura mater and the vertebral canal. Inflammation or infection here would be termed epiduritis or epidural abscess, presenting with different symptoms and requiring different management approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubarachnoid space\u003C/strong\u003E contains cerebrospinal fluid and is bounded by the arachnoid and pia mater. Inflammation here would constitute meningitis rather than myelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural space\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential space between the dura and arachnoid mater. Pathology here typically presents as subdural haematoma or hygroma, not inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these anatomical distinctions is crucial as each space can be affected by different pathological processes requiring specific diagnostic approaches and treatments. Myelitis requires investigations for autoimmune, infectious, or paraneoplastic causes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myelitis refers to inflammation of the spinal cord parenchyma.","The suffix \u0027-itis\u0027 refers to inflammation of the structure named in the root word.","Distinguishing between inflammation of the spinal cord and its surrounding structures is crucial for accurate diagnosis and treatment."],"references":["Beh SC, Greenberg BM, Frohman T, Frohman EM. Transverse myelitis. Neurol Clin. 2013 Feb;31(1):79-138. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2012.09.008. PMID: 23186897; PMCID: PMC7132741.","Lim PAC. Transverse Myelitis. Essentials of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation. 2020:952\u20139. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-54947-9.00162-0. Epub 2019 Apr 17. PMCID: PMC7151963.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60343"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16470"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60343"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T17:17:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T17:17:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9161"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i